div.p:
Attend now and I will rehearse some compound remedies against disease. Grind down and take the strength-giving Sicilian root of fustic;
add a heap of the seed of the bright-flowered agnus castus, savin, and the luxuriant rue, and pluck a shoot of the earth-pillowed savory, which in the forest spreads abroad fronds like those of the tufted thyme. Again take the root of the double-flowered asphodel, or else the upper portion of its stem; often with them too the seed which the enclosing pod ripens; or else helxine, which men call Clybatis and which delights in streams and flourishes ever in water-meadows. Drink them after crumbling them into a cotyle of vinegar or of wine which you have drawn.
Even with water you might easily escape death.
